{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17642412","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17642412"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:40:07+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:40:07+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17941"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17941","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17941"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.37,0.11,0.44,0.07,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10655"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72981"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10655","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10655"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17941"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58451"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4901"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"7304"},{"type":"tags","id":"7305"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24823"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24827"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72981","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/72981"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe occiput is a part of the skull that plays a crucial role in the articulation with the first cervical vertebra, known as the atlas (C1).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following landmarks of the occiput is responsible for articulation with the atlas (C1)?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Foramen magnum","External occipital protuberance","Occipital condyles","Basilar part","Hypoglossal canal"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eoccipital condyles\u003C/strong\u003E are the rounded projections on the occiput that articulate with the superior articular facets of the atlas (C1) vertebra. This joint allows for the nodding motion of the head.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other options are not involved in this articulation:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EForamen magnum\u003C/strong\u003E - This is the large opening in the occiput through which the spinal cord passes.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExternal occipital protuberance\u003C/strong\u003E - This is a bony prominence on the back of the skull, not involved in articulation with the atlas.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBasilar part\u003C/strong\u003E - This is the part of the occipital bone that extends forward from the foramen magnum, not involved in articulation with the atlas.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHypoglossal canal\u003C/strong\u003E - This is a passageway for the hypoglossal nerve, not involved in articulation with the atlas.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The occipital condyles are the structures on the occiput that articulate with the atlas (C1) vertebra.","The articulation between the occipital condyles and the atlas allows for nodding movements of the head.","The foramen magnum is a large opening in the occiput for the passage of the spinal cord."],"references":["Singh, V. (2023). Textbook of Anatomy-Head, Neck and Brain, Volume III-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Patestas, M. A., \u0026 Gartner, L. P. (2016). A textbook of neuroanatomy. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Patel, C. R., Fernandez-Miranda, J. C., Wang, W. H., \u0026 Wang, E. W. (2016). Skull Base Anatomy. Otolaryngologic clinics of North America, 49(1), 9\u201320. https://doi.org/10.1016/j.otc.2015.09.001","Anderson, B. W., Kortz, M. W., Black, A. C., \u0026 Al Kharazi, K. A. (2023). Anatomy, Head and Neck, Skull. In StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58451"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17941"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58451","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/58451"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-22T23:47:34+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-22T23:48:19+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10655"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72981"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4901","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4901"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Anatomy of the neck","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-13T18:31:29+10:30","updatedAt":"